 to deliver work experience\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIt provides information about a range of government programmes and how you can get involved. It includes details on each programme and useful resources about planning placements, health and safety, pay and quality.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"benefits-of-offering-work-experience-and-workplace-learning-opportunities\"\u003eBenefits of offering work experience and workplace learning opportunities\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eEmployers highlight these benefits:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003estaff development - existing staff can develop supervisory, coaching and management skills\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003eraised public profile and improved recruitment - by helping people into employment\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003econtribution to corporate social responsibility - by reducing social problems such as ill-health and poverty that are linked to unemployment\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003econtribution to social mobility - by supporting young people disadvantaged by their background who can use work experience to secure sustainable employment\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003eincreasing diversity - giving work experience opportunities to people from a wide range of backgrounds can lead to a more diverse workforce, and the benefits that brings, such as engaging better with a range of customers\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eWork experience is an effective way to prepare young people and adults for employment. It can help to:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003einform career choices\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003eget people back into work\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003edevelop technical skills\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003edevelop the attitudes and behaviours expected at work\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"work-experience-and-workplace-training-programmes\"\u003eWork experience and workplace training programmes\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSome of these programmes may cover more than one age group.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"up-to-19\"\u003eUp to 19\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 id=\"work-experience-for-school-students-14-to-16\"\u003eWork experience for school students: 14 to 16\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAge: 14 to 16 \u003cbr\u003e\nTypical placement length: 1 to 2 weeks \u003cbr\u003e\nWage required: no  \u003cbr\u003e\nResponsibility: school or college, students \u003cbr\u003e\nAvailability: England \u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eMany schools and students arrange work placements with employers during years 10 and 11. Work placements aim to give students experience of the workplace before they leave school.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eEmployer guidance on good practice in providing effective placements, and the effects on learners and employers, is available in section 8.1 of the report on \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/work-experience-and-related-activities-in-schools-and-colleges\"\u003eWork experience and related activities in schools and colleges\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/\"\u003eContact schools and colleges\u003c/a\u003e directly if you would like to provide a placement, or work with \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.careersandenterprise.co.uk/employers\"\u003eThe Careers and Enterprise Company to promote work experience opportunities\u003c/a\u003e (see below).\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 id=\"working-with-the-careers-and-enterprise-company\"\u003eWorking with The Careers and Enterprise Company\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAge: 11 to 18 \u003cbr\u003e\nTypical length: various between 1 hour and 2 weeks \u003cbr\u003e\nWage required: no  \u003cbr\u003e\nResponsibility: The Careers and Enterprise Company, schools and colleges \u003cbr\u003e\nAvailability: England \u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe Careers and Enterprise Company helps to inspire and prepare young people for work. It links schools and colleges to employers through its Enterprise Advisor Network. You can:\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cul\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003epromote your existing work experience opportunities for young people through The Careers and Enterprise Company’s network of Enterprise Co-ordinators\u003c/li\u003e\n  \u003cli\u003evolunteer as an individual to become an Enterprise Adviser and work directly with a local school or college to increase engagement with business\u003c/li\u003e\n\u003c/ul\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFind out more in \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.careersandenterprise.co.uk/employers\"\u003eThe Careers and Enterprise Company’s employers guide\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 id=\"work-experience-for-students-aged-16-to-19-study-programmes\"\u003eWork experience for students aged 16 to 19: study programmes\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAge: 16 to 19 \u003cbr\u003e\nTypical placement length: varies typically from 2 to 8 weeks  \u003cbr\u003e\nWage required: no  \u003cbr\u003e\nResponsibility: schools, colleges and training providers\u003cbr\u003e\nAvailability: England \u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eStudy programmes aim to help young people gain experience of the workplace, and to develop the skills that employers need.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eMost study programmes have a core aim, which is a substantial qualification, either academic or vocational, or work experience. Work experience is a key component of study programmes for 16- to 19-year-olds, typically to \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/what-different-qualification-levels-mean/list-of-qualification-levels\"\u003elevel 3\u003c/a\u003e (qualifications such as \u003cabbr title=\"General Certificate of Education Advanced level\"\u003eA levels\u003c/abbr\u003e, \u003cabbr title=\"General Certificate of Education Advanced Subsidiary level\"\u003eAS levels\u003c/abbr\u003e, \u003cabbr title=\"higher education\"\u003eHE\u003c/abbr\u003e diplomas).\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.compare-school-performance.service.gov.uk/\"\u003eContact schools, colleges\u003c/a\u003e or \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.ukrlp.co.uk/\"\u003etraining providers\u003c/a\u003e directly if you would like to provide a placement, or \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.careersandenterprise.co.uk/employers\"\u003ework with The Careers and Enterprise Company\u003c/a\u003e to promote work experience opportunities. You may find it useful to read our \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/16-to-19-study-programmes-guide-for-providers\"\u003e16 to 19 study programmes: guide for training providers\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 id=\"t-level-industry-placements\"\u003eT Level industry placements\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAge: 16 to 18 \u003cbr\u003e\nTypical placement length: minimum 45 days \u003cbr\u003e\nWage required: no \u003cbr\u003e\nResponsibility: training providers\u003cbr\u003e\nAvailability: England \u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eT Levels are 2-year technical programmes for young people aged 16 to 19 and will be available from 2020. They will offer a mix of classroom and workplace experience. Industry placements are being steadily implemented across England preceding the \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/introduction-of-t-levels/introduction-of-t-levels\"\u003eT Level rollout\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eRead the \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.aoc.co.uk/industry-placements-guidance-resources\"\u003eAssociation of College’s employer factsheets\u003c/a\u003e about the benefits of vocational industry placements.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eContact the National Apprenticeship Service (\u003cabbr title=\"National Apprenticeship Service\"\u003eNAS\u003c/abbr\u003e) employer helpline if you need more information about T Levels and industry placements. Call 0800 015 0600 (free calls from landlines and mobiles) or email \u003ca href=\"mailto:TLevel.Placement@education.gov.uk\"\u003eTLevel.Placement@education.gov.uk\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"to-24\"\u003e16 to 24\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 id=\"supported-internships-for-young-people-with-an-education-health-and-care-ehc-plan\"\u003eSupported internships for young people with an education, health and care (\u003cabbr title=\"education, health and care\"\u003eEHC\u003c/abbr\u003e) plan\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAge: 16 to 24 \u003cbr\u003e\nTypical placement length: 6 months+ \u003cbr\u003e\nWage required: no  \u003cbr\u003e\nResponsibility: education and training providers \u003cbr\u003e\nAvailability: England \u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSupported internships are structured study programmes that aim to help young people with learning difficulties and/or disability to achieve sustainable, paid employment by equipping them with the skills they need for work through learning in the workplace.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eRead Preparing for Adulthood’s guide about the value of \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.preparingforadulthood.org.uk/downloads/employment/work-experience-guidance.htm\"\u003ework experience for young people with special educational needs and disability (\u003cabbr title=\"special educational needs and disability\"\u003eSEND\u003c/abbr\u003e)\u003c/a\u003e, and how to support them on a positive pathway to employment.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 id=\"traineeships\"\u003eTraineeships\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAge: 16 to 24 \u003cbr\u003e\nTypical placement length: varies between 100 to 240 hours \u003cbr\u003e\nWage required: no  \u003cbr\u003e\nResponsibility: colleges and training providers \u003cbr\u003e\nAvailability: England \u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eTraineeships offer a combination of work experience, work preparation training, and English and maths where needed. Trainees can also undertake additional content if needed, such as technical and professional qualifications or mentoring. You can bring these elements together with the Traineeship provider in a way that best meets the needs of the young person to equip them to work in your company or sector.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eRead the \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/guidance/traineeships\"\u003etraineeships programme overview for employers\u003c/a\u003e about how to get involved.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"section\"\u003e18+\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 id=\"prisoners-and-ex-offenders\"\u003ePrisoners and ex-offenders\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAge: 18+ \u003cbr\u003e\nTypical placement length: 2 weeks + \u003cbr\u003e\nWage required: yes \u003cbr\u003e\nResponsibility: \u003cabbr title=\"Her Majesty's\"\u003eHM\u003c/abbr\u003e Prison and Probation Service \u003cbr\u003e\nAvailability: England and Wales \u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eA third of prisoners have a job in prison. This could include cooking in the kitchens, cleaning on the prison wings or cutting hair at the barber.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eRelease on temporary licence (\u003cabbr title=\"release on temporary licence\"\u003eROTL\u003c/abbr\u003e) allows prisoners, who have been properly risk-assessed, out of their cells and into real workplaces. This allows prisoners to build trust and prove themselves with an employer.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFind out about the benefits, and \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/unlock-opportunity-employer-information-pack-and-case-studies\"\u003ehow to employ prisoners and ex-offenders on work experience\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 id=\"jobcentre-plus-work-experience\"\u003eJobcentre Plus: work experience\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAge: 18+ (some 16- and 17-year-olds on benefits can also participate)  \u003cbr\u003e\nTypical placement length: 2 to 8 weeks  \u003cbr\u003e\nWage required: no  \u003cbr\u003e\nResponsibility: Jobcentre Plus  \u003cbr\u003e\nAvailability: Great Britain \u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eUnemployed people can volunteer for placements. These volunteers are matched with suitable host employers and complete a light-touch selection process.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/employers-could-you-offer-work-experience\"\u003eJobcentre Plus employer guide for offering work experience\u003c/a\u003e covers induction, supporting participants, feedback and exit interviews, job search support, mentoring, buddying and shadowing. It also includes information about registering to provide work experience through Jobcentre Plus.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 id=\"jobcentre-plus-youth-obligation-support-programme-work-placements\"\u003eJobcentre Plus: youth obligation support programme work placements\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAge: 18 to 21 \u003cbr\u003e\nTypical placement length: 3 months \u003cbr\u003e\nWage required: no \u003cbr\u003e\nResponsibility: Jobcentre Plus  \u003cbr\u003e\nAvailability: Great Britain \u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe youth obligation support programme offers intensive support for 18- to 21-year-olds making a new claim to \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/universal-credit\"\u003eUniversal Credit\u003c/a\u003e. Claimants can opt for a range of different training and work experience opportunities. For those still claiming after 6 months, this includes a specific guaranteed 3-month work placement. The goal is to prevent young people from moving into long-term unemployment.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eRead information about the support available for claimants, including the guaranteed work experience placement in \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/guidance/support-for-18-to-21-year-olds-claiming-universal-credit#work-experience\"\u003eSupport for 18- to 21-year-olds claiming Universal Credit\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 id=\"jobcentre-plus-sector-based-work-academies\"\u003eJobcentre Plus: sector-based work academies\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAge: All ages, from 18 years \u003cbr\u003e\nTypical placement length: 2 to 6 weeks  \u003cbr\u003e\nWage required: no \u003cbr\u003e\nResponsibility: Jobcentre Plus  \u003cbr\u003e\nAvailability: England and Scotland \u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSector-based work academies provide pre-employment training, work experience and a guaranteed job interview to unemployed benefit claimants of any age. Placements are arranged by Jobcentre Plus, last up to 6 weeks and can help to meet employers’ recruitment needs.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eRead \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/sector-based-work-academies-employer-guide\"\u003eSector-based work academies: employer guide\u003c/a\u003e for information about how Jobcentre Plus can help employers fill their vacancies more efficiently.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 id=\"jobcentre-plus-work-trials\"\u003eJobcentre Plus: work trials\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAge: 18+ \u003cbr\u003e\nTypical placement length: 5 to 30 days (unpaid work trials cannot be longer than 30 days by law) \u003cbr\u003e\nWage required: no  \u003cbr\u003e\nResponsibility: Jobcentre Plus  \u003cbr\u003e\nAvailability: Great Britain \u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eA work trial is a way of assessing a potential employee after conditionally offering them a job. Participants remain on benefits during the trial period which typically lasts a week. You can only offer this to unemployed benefit claimants aged 18+ and you must \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/jobcentre-plus-help-for-recruiters/work-trials\"\u003earrange a work trial with Jobcentre Plus\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 id=\"higher-education-placements\"\u003eHigher education placements\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAge: 18+ \u003cbr\u003e\nTypical placement length: 1 month to 1 year \u003cbr\u003e\nWage required: depends on employment status - [advice on pay]\u003cbr\u003e(https://www.gov.uk/guidance/national-minimum-wage-work-experience-and-internships)\u003cbr\u003e\nResponsibility: employer and university or higher education provider \u003cbr\u003e\nAvailability: United Kingdom \u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eYou can offer university and college students various types of work experience, such as a summer internship, sandwich placement, placement year or a year in industry. These can be compulsory or voluntary components of undergraduate and graduate courses. These placements can help identify future employees.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/check-a-university-is-officially-recognised/recognised-bodies\"\u003eContact universities and colleges\u003c/a\u003e for further information.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch4 id=\"graduate-talent-pool\"\u003eGraduate talent pool\u003c/h4\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eAge: Typically 21+ \u003cbr\u003e\nTypical placement length: 1 to 12 months  \u003cbr\u003e\nWage required: yes - all advertisements must be for paid vacancies \u003cbr\u003e\nResponsibility: employer \u003cbr\u003e\nAvailability: United Kingdom \u003cbr\u003e\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eGraduate talent pool (\u003cabbr title=\"graduate talent pool\"\u003eGTP\u003c/abbr\u003e) is a government website where employers can advertise graduate internship positions.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cabbr title=\"graduate talent pool\"\u003eGTP\u003c/abbr\u003e provides a matching service, where you can connect with graduates who are seeking an internship.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eIt provides case studies for employers and links to an employer advice service on setting up internships.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eGo to the \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://graduatetalentpoolsearch.direct.gov.uk/gtp/information-for-employers\"\u003egraduate talent pool employer page\u003c/a\u003e for more information.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch2 id=\"further-information-and-guidance\"\u003eFurther information and guidance\u003c/h2\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eA range of further information, guidance and related initiatives exist that can help employers to deliver high-quality work experience or placements. Some of these are included below.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"employer-groups-and-commitments\"\u003eEmployer groups and commitments\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.movementtowork.com/\"\u003eMovement to work\u003c/a\u003e is a charity, and voluntary collaboration of UK employers, committed to reducing youth unemployment by providing high-quality work experience and vocational training opportunities for young people not in education, employment or training (\u003cabbr title=\"not in education, employment or training\"\u003eNEET\u003c/abbr\u003e).\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/see-potential-case-studies-and-employer-information-pack\"\u003eSee Potential\u003c/a\u003e is a campaign that encourages employers to give people from different backgrounds the opportunity to work and turn their lives around. These can include long-term unemployed people, ex-offenders, care leavers, recovering addicts, homeless people, single parents and military veterans.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"guidance-on-delivering-work-experience\"\u003eGuidance on delivering work experience\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eRead Preparing for Adulthood’s guidance on \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.preparingforadulthood.org.uk/downloads/employment/work-experience-guidance.htm\"\u003ehow to support young people with special educational needs and disability\u003c/a\u003e (\u003cabbr title=\"special educational needs and disability\"\u003eSEND\u003c/abbr\u003e) through work experience.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eReturner programmes are for people returning to work after a long break (typically 2 years or more) for caring or other reasons. Read \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/set-up-a-returner-programme\"\u003eguidance for employers on developing and delivering effective returner programmes\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eRead research about companies which have successfully offered work experience in \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/not-just-making-tea-a-guide-to-work-experience\"\u003eNot just making tea - reinventing work experience\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eThe Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development’s (\u003cabbr title=\"Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development\"\u003eCIPD\u003c/abbr\u003e) \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.cipd.co.uk/knowledge/fundamentals/people/routes-work/work-experience-guide\"\u003eMaking work experience work: top tips for employers\u003c/a\u003e highlights good recruitment practices and provides information on giving feedback during placements.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003cabbr title=\"Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development\"\u003eCIPD\u003c/abbr\u003e’s \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.cipd.co.uk/knowledge/fundamentals/people/routes-work/internships-guide\"\u003eSetting up or improving an internship scheme\u003c/a\u003e includes information about recruiting and supervising participants.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eRead government guidance on \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/providing-quality-internships-code-and-guidance-for-employers\"\u003eProviding quality internships: guidance for employers and interns\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"quality-standards\"\u003eQuality standards\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eFind out about \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.fairtrain.org/\"\u003eFair Train and their work experience quality standard\u003c/a\u003e and \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.youthemployment.org.uk/youth-friendly-employer-award/\"\u003eYouth Employment UK’s Youth Friendly Employer Award\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"pay\"\u003ePay\u003c/h3\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eRead \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/guidance/national-minimum-wage-work-experience-and-internships\"\u003eguidance on pay for organisations offering work experience\u003c/a\u003e. Specific guidance is also available on \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/employment-rights-for-interns\"\u003eemployment rights and pay for interns\u003c/a\u003e - many interns fall within the definition of ‘worker’ and are legally entitled to the \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/national-minimum-wage\"\u003enational minimum and living wage\u003c/a\u003e.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"health-and-safety\"\u003eHealth and safety\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eUnder health and safety law, there is no requirement for a separate risk assessment for work experience students, as employers should already be managing any \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hse.gov.uk/youngpeople/workexperience/index.htm\"\u003ehealth and safety risks\u003c/a\u003e in their workplaces. To ensure young people have their health and safety protected in the workplace, read Health and Safety Executive’s (\u003cabbr title=\"Health and Safety Executive\"\u003eHSE\u003c/abbr\u003e) \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hse.gov.uk/pubns/indg364.htm\"\u003eYoung people and work experience\u003c/a\u003e guidance for employers.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"employers-liability-insurance\"\u003eEmployers’ liability insurance\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003e\u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.hse.gov.uk/youngpeople/faqs.htm\"\u003e\u003cabbr title=\"Health and Safety Executive\"\u003eHSE\u003c/abbr\u003e young people at work guidance\u003c/a\u003e and the \u003ca rel=\"external\" href=\"https://www.abi.org.uk/products-and-issues/choosing-the-right-insurance/business-insurance/liability-insurance/employers-liability-insurance/work-experience-students/\"\u003eAssociation of British Insurers (ABI) work experience students guidance\u003c/a\u003e explains that if you already have \u003ca href=\"https://www.gov.uk/employers-liability-insurance\"\u003eemployers’ liability insurance\u003c/a\u003e cover, you do not need to buy additional cover for work experience placements, provided the insurer is a member of the ABI or Lloyds. If in doubt, please check with your insurer for any additional cover for other types of work experience for young adults, people with special educational needs and disability (\u003cabbr title=\"special educational needs and disability\"\u003eSEND\u003c/abbr\u003e) or young offenders.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003ch3 id=\"sector-representative-information\"\u003eSector-representative information\u003c/h3\u003e\n\n\u003cp\u003eSearch online for employer guides by sector bodies and umbrella organisations for specific advice or additional best practice guidance.\u003c/p\u003e\n\n\u003c/div\u003e","about":[{"@context":"http://schema.org","@type":"Thing","sameAs":"https://www.gov.uk/education/hiring-and-training-and-intern-or-trainee"},{"@context":"http://schema.org","@type":"Thing","sameAs":"https://www.gov.uk/education/support-for-special-educational-needs-and-disability-send"},{"@context":"http://schema.org","@type":"Thing","sameAs":"https://www.gov.uk/employment/recruiting-hiring"}]}
